<section id="glossary">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div>
        <div class="kicker">Glossary for fast reading</div>
        <h2>Technical language translated, not removed.</h2>
      </div>
      <p>A short glossary reduces editorial friction for terms central to the manuscript but not yet familiar to all reviewers.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="panel glossary-card">
        <h4>Mesoscale scaffold</h4>
        <p>The relatively stable community structure of the symptom network. Here, it refers to the broad modular organization that persists even when influence shifts across phases.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel glossary-card">
        <h4>Minimum dominating set (MDS)</h4>
        <p>The smallest set of nodes that covers the whole graph directly or through neighbors. It provides a concrete way to define which symptoms can serve as drivers in the network.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel glossary-card">
        <h4>Control frequency (CF)</h4>
        <p>The proportion of exact minimum dominating sets in which a symptom appears. A high CF means the symptom repeatedly participates in minimal driver solutions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel glossary-card">
        <h4>Average control frequency (ACF)</h4>
        <p>The average normalized control frequency within a module or domain. Informative descriptively, but less stable under case loss than AMCS.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="panel glossary-card">
        <h4>Average module control strength (AMCS)</h4>
        <p>A directed summary of how strongly one symptom module dominates another. The manuscript's key mesoscale comparison metric and the most important control graphic to foreground.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

